04712nam a22006975i 9780691187488DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911874887 a10.1515/97806911874882doi  a(DE-B1597)501834  a(OCoLC)1076450650  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBM292b.R93 2000eb 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a296/.0942/090342231 aRuderman, David B., eauthor.10aJewish Enlightenment in an English Key :bAnglo-Jewry's Construction of Modern Jewish Thought /cDavid B. Ruderman. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. "The Scripture Correcting Maniae":1 Benjamin Kennicott and His Hutchinsonian and Anglo-Jewish Detractors -- tTwo. The New and "Metrical5 5 English Bible: Robert Lowth and His Jewish Critic, David Levi -- tThree. Deism and Its Reverberations in English Jewish Thought: Abraham Ben Naphtali Tang and Some of His Contemporaries -- tFour. Between Rational and Irrational Dissent: Political Radicalism in Anglo-Jewish Thought -- tFive. Science and Newtonianism in the Culture of Anglo-Jewry -- tSix. Translation and Transformation: The Englishing of Jewish Culture -- tAfterword -- tAppendix. Moses Mendelssohn through Anglo-Jewish Eyes -- tIndex  aHistorians of the European Jewish experience have long marginalized the intellectual achievement of Jews in England, where it was assumed no seminal figures contributed to the development of modern Jewish thought. In this first comprehensive account of the emergence of Anglo-Jewish thought in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries, David Ruderman impels a reconsideration of the formative beginnings of modern European Jewish culture. He uncovers a vibrant Jewish intellectual life in England during the Enlightenment era by examining a small but fascinating group of hitherto neglected Jewish thinkers in the process of transforming their traditional Hebraic culture into a modern English one. This lively portrait of English Jews reformulating their tradition in light of Enlightenment categories illuminates an overlooked corner in the history of Jewish culture in England and Jewish thought during the Enlightenment. Ruderman overturns the conventional view that the origins of modern Jewish consciousness are located exclusively within the German-Jewish experience, particularly Moses Mendelssohn's circle. Independent of the better-known German experience, the encounter between Jewish and English thought was incubated amid the unprecedented freedom enjoyed by Jews in England. This resulted in a less inhibited defense of Jews and Judaism. In addition to the original and prolific thinkers David Levi and Abraham Tang, Ruderman introduces Abraham and Joshua Van Oven, Mordechai Shnaber Levison, Samuel Falk, Isaac Delgado, Solomon Bennett, Hyman Hurwitz, Emanuel Mendes da Costa, Ralph Shomberg, and others. Of obvious appeal and import to students of Jewish and English history, this study depicts the challenge of defining a religious identity in the modern age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aJewszGreat BritainxIntellectual lifey18th century. 0aJudaismzGreat BritainxHistoryy18th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187488zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187488.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  